Reason carefully about the fundamental trade-off between detection precision and developer usability in code smell detection systems. A code smell detector faces a dilemma: if it sets thresholds conservatively (high bar for flagging), it misses real problems and developers learn to ignore it when it does fire. If it sets thresholds aggressively (low bar), it floods developers with false positives and they disable it entirely. The literature suggests that even expert developers disagree on whether code has a smell roughly 30-40% of the time, which creates a ceiling on achievable precision.

Think through the following dimensions of this trade-off. First, how does the optimal precision/recall operating point differ depending on the use context: a blocking CI gate that fails builds, a non-blocking advisory report, an IDE annotation shown while coding, and a weekly trend report shown to a tech lead? Second, is it better to have a small set of high-precision rules with very low false positive rates, or a large set of imprecise rules that developers can configure? What does the research on developer adoption of linting tools say about this? Third, how does the smell type affect the optimal threshold: for Long Method the threshold is a number (lines of code), but for Feature Envy the detection is inherently heuristic — should these be presented with different confidence levels? Fourth, consider the specific problem of threshold tuning for a multi-language tool: if the Long Method threshold is set at 50 lines and this generates 200 warnings in the Python codebase but only 10 in the Go codebase (because Go functions tend to be shorter), should the threshold be calibrated per-language using population percentiles from open-source data? Reason through what the right calibration methodology would be and what data you would need.
